{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567795","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567795"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:07:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:07:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19384"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19384","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19384"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.02,0.1,0.64,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12111"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96754"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12111","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12111"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19384"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79369"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3645"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4984"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11701"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"28641"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33132"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44998"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96754","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96754"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic seeking pre-travel advice. He is planning a three-month backpacking trip through central Africa, including Uganda and Tanzania. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He has heard about schistosomiasis (bilharzia) and is concerned about contracting the infection during his travels.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate advice to prevent schistosomiasis infection?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Drink only bottled or boiled water","Receive pre-travel vaccination","Take prophylactic praziquantel before travel","Avoid swimming in fresh water","Apply insect repellent before swimming"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESchistosomiasis is a parasitic infection caused by blood flukes of the genus \u003Cem\u003ESchistosoma \u003C/em\u003Ewhich is endemic in many African countries and in South America. Whilst most patients are asymptomatic (80%), patients may develop long term complications such as portal hypertension from intrahepatic periportal fibrosis or massive spleenomegaly. The parasite is transmitted through contact with fresh water containing infected snails that release schistosomal cercariae, which can penetrate human skin. Understanding the transmission cycle is crucial for prevention.  Schistosomiasis serology can confirm the diagnosis and stool and urinalysis testing done for further investigation and confirm eradication. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAvoiding swimming in fresh water\u003C/strong\u003E is the most effective preventive measure. This includes not swimming, wading, or bathing in potentially contaminated fresh water sources such as lakes, rivers, and streams in endemic areas. If contact with fresh water is unavoidable, wearing protective boots or waders can help reduce risk.  Wearing swimming suits would not be protective as there would still be exposed skin to the cerciae.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETaking prophylactic praziquantel\u003C/strong\u003E before travel is not recommended as it is not effective in preventing infection. Praziquantel is used to treat established infections, typically given 6-8 weeks in two doses after exposure when adult worms have developed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EApplying insect repellent\u003C/strong\u003E before swimming would not prevent schistosomiasis as the cercariae can penetrate skin regardless of repellent application. Insect repellents are ineffective against the aquatic larvae.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrinking only bottled or boiled water\u003C/strong\u003E will not prevent schistosomiasis as the infection is not transmitted through drinking water. This advice would help prevent other water-borne illnesses but not schistosomiasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReceiving pre-travel vaccination\u003C/strong\u003E is not possible as there is currently no vaccine available for schistosomiasis. Research into vaccine development is ongoing but none are currently approved for use.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Schistosomiasis is transmitted through contact with fresh water containing infected snails.","Prevention of schistosomiasis involves avoiding contact with potentially contaminated fresh water.","There is no vaccine or chemoprophylaxis available for schistosomiasis prevention."],"references":["Rinaldi G, Young ND, Honeycutt JD, et al. New Research Tools for Urogenital Schistosomiasis. J Infect Dis. 2014; 211:861\u201369.","Benson J. Asymptomatic schistosomiasis in a young Sudanese refugee.  Australian Family Physician. 2007:  36 (4).  Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/a26f4e0d-deed-4037-a553-d2c79d4ab13c/attachment.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79369"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19384"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79369","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79369"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T21:17:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T21